The abduction of the music-girl was not on account of AEschinus himself, but for his brother. Endeavours had been used to obtain her fairly from Sanni03 but he insisted upon conditions which it wan impossible for them to comply with. This reduced Ctesipho to the greatest despair, insomuch that he was on the point of leaving his country. AEscfflnus, seeing the consequences were likely to prove so terrible, resolves upon violence, and, as we have seen, carries the girl off by force. Ctesipho had by this time heard of it, and is here introduced full of joy at his good fortune, and of gratitude to a brother who had done so much for him.
